Your daily round-up of the best of the Journal’s China coverage:
China’s Transparency Standards Collide With U.S. Investor Expectations: Here’s something U.S. investors in Chinese companies shouldn’t expect to be told: Whether relatives of senior politicians number among the executives, as they often do. (Free)
Beijing’s Grand Visions for Financial Hub: A new financial center planned for Beijing aims to defy doubters on the sustainability of China’s real-estate boom and the stability of its overstretched banks. (Free)
Posttrial, Bo Still Shines With Base: Communist Party efforts to scrub away Bo Xilai’s popular image have yet to dim support for the disgraced political star in the western Chinese municipality he governed. (Subscriber Content)
China Communist Party Plans Key November Meeting: China’s Communist Party will hold a key meeting of senior officials in November to discuss major policies on the country’s reform agenda, the official Xinhua News Agency said. (Subscriber Content)
China Extends Graft Probes to PetroChina: State-controlled PetroChina Co. said three of its senior executives are under investigation by authorities for “severe disciplinary violations” and have resigned, as Chinese authorities seem to be ratcheting up efforts to root out official corruption. (Subscriber Content)
